WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.320
Okay, in an effort to keep us on time,

2
00:00:03.260 --> 00:00:05.100
I'm Louis Chodosh. I have

3
00:00:05.960 --> 00:00:07.260
the honor of

4
00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:12.160
chairing today's session, Advances in Understanding Disseminated Tumor Cells:

5
00:00:12.740 --> 00:00:16.130
An Emerging Opportunity to Prevent Lethal Breast

6
00:00:16.220 --> 00:00:20.170
Cancer? With a question mark and the emphasis, I suppose, on

7
00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:20.960
the question mark.

8
00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:23.520
I'm from the University of Pennsylvania.

9
00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:26.919
I will introduce our speakers momentarily.

10
00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:31.380
So by way of introduction, the focus of this session is on

11
00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:33.580
this problem, breast cancer recurrence.

12
00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:37.560
So we all know breast cancer is the most common cancer

13
00:00:37.660 --> 00:00:41.140
diagnosed amongst men or women. And fortunately,

14
00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:44.900
five-year survival is quite good, approaching 90%.

15
00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:49.120
And as a consequence, breast cancer is by far the most prevalent

16
00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:52.760
cancer in the world, with more than 12 million breast cancer

17
00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:56.560
survivors globally. The majority of women

18
00:00:56.680 --> 00:01:00.560
are in what we would call a no evidence of disease period,

19
00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:04.511
or the surveillance period, in which there

20
00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:07.780
is nothing. There is no disease evident on a

21
00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:11.550
scan. However, in following patients,

22
00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:15.660
up to 30% of women will ultimately recur

23
00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:20.200
following a variable latency period, and that recurrence,

24
00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:24.080
typically metastatic recurrence, is responsible for nearly all

25
00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:28.040
mortality from this disease. Now, breast cancer recurrence

26
00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:32.320
has the interesting property shared with prostate cancer in

27
00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:36.040
which recurrences can happen after many years.

28
00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:39.950
So in some cases, 25 years or more after

29
00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:42.080
definitive treatment of the primary tumor.

30
00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:46.040
And while these sorts of kinetics are typically

31
00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:50.090
associated with estrogen receptor positive breast cancers, it

32
00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:54.020
is also seen to some degree with estrogen receptor-negative tumors as

33
00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:57.540
well. And this very long stochastic

34
00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:01.150
latency period has brought up the question of whether

35
00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:04.320
these cancers may pass through a dormant phase.

36
00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:09.179
Now, arguably, the current clinical approach to breast cancer is

37
00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:13.100
front-end loaded. That is, there is definitive treatment of the

38
00:02:13.109 --> 00:02:17.060
primary tumor. Women enter the surveillance period, and there are

39
00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:20.940
really very few therapeutic interventions during that

40
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.320
surveillance period to prevent recurrence other than

41
00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:28.200
anti-estrogen therapies and CDK4/6 inhibitors

42
00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:31.829
for ER positive breast cancers. Now, during this

43
00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:35.200
period, patients are observed. There's no active monitoring.

44
00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:39.580
There's no clinical test that will tell you whether

45
00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:43.240
a woman is part of the 30% who might ultimately recur.

46
00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:47.810
And this causes a lot of anxiety, understandably, and

47
00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:51.829
decreased quality of life for patients because they can never

48
00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:53.680
know whether they're cured or not.

49
00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:58.640
So I would argue that the failure to intervene during the surveillance period is a

50
00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:02.680
missed opportunity, that simply watchful waiting is not enough.

51
00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:05.120
So why do some breast cancers recur?

52
00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:08.769
Well, as one of our speakers, Christoph Klein, and others have shown,

53
00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:13.180
over the period of years in which a breast cancer grows to reach a clinically

54
00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:17.180
detectable size, there are cancer cells that make their way into

55
00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:20.740
the bloodstream, disseminate to distant organs, and can

56
00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:24.500
basically sit there as single cells or micro metastases as

57
00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:27.240
DTCs or minimal residual disease.

58
00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:31.600
And at some point, in some women, DTCs can reactivate growth

59
00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:34.480
and give rise to recurrent metastatic cancers.

60
00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:38.440
So DTCs are the reservoir from which

61
00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:42.220
recurrent tumors arise. And again, the fact that they can survive in their

62
00:03:42.260 --> 00:03:46.080
host for decades raises the question of whether they pass through a

63
00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:46.840
dormant phase.

64
00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:51.170
So if one looks at bone marrow aspirates in early-stage breast cancer patients,

65
00:03:51.620 --> 00:03:55.580
up to 40% will have detectable DTCs in their bone marrow,

66
00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:59.560
shown here by pancytokeratin immunohistochemistry.

67
00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:03.920
And that's important because the presence of DTCs in

68
00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:07.600
early-stage patients is strongly associated with an

69
00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:11.640
increased risk of recurrence and decreased overall survival, as

70
00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:15.260
you might expect for cells in this reservoir

71
00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:19.360
that gives rise to recurrence. So DTCs are really both a

72
00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:23.300
biomarker to identify early-stage patients who have an increased

73
00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:27.000
risk for recurrence, and we can also think of them as a

74
00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:30.610
potential therapeutic target, as we'll talk about in today's session.

75
00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:35.080
And I would say the main questions that we have to answer to get to that

76
00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:39.080
type of clinical approach is, first, what are the biological properties

77
00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:42.640
of DTCs? What are the mechanisms by which they persist and

78
00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:46.500
recur? And can we translate that information to prevent

79
00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:50.140
recurrence? And today, we have three speakers who will address

80
00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:52.920
each of those particular questions.

81
00:04:53.300 --> 00:04:56.960
So I will speak first about approaches to clinical

82
00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.580
translation targeting DTCs. Then we will

83
00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:04.160
have Dr. Amoya Sreekumar, who is one of the

84
00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:08.020
AACR NextGen Stars, who will talk about a particularly

85
00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.410
interesting mechanism by which dormancy is enforced

86
00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:14.900
in tumor cells. And then we will have Dr.

87
00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:19.060
Christoph Klein from the University of Regensburg in Germany, who

88
00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:22.740
will talk to us about the biology and molecular characteristics

89
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.500
of patient-derived disseminated tumor cells.

90
00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:30.320
So with that, I will start my talk.

91
00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:35.340
These are my disclosures. Okay, so if really

92
00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:39.180
all breast cancer mortality or the vast majority is

93
00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:43.120
due to lethal recurrent breast cancers, the goal of

94
00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:46.840
preventing breast cancer mortality could presumably be achieved by

95
00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:49.580
preventing recurrence, if that's the lethal event.

96
00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:54.020
And the strategy that I'm going to talk about is depleting this reservoir

97
00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:57.660
of DTCs or at least preventing them from reactivating.

98
00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:00.990
And the approach, as I mentioned earlier, is really to say,

99
00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:05.800
look at DTCs as bothThe prognostic marker of risk

100
00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:09.780
and the target for therapy. And the steps are:

101
00:06:09.860 --> 00:06:13.680
understand the mechanisms of dormancy and reactivation in these cells,

102
00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:18.380
develop better methods to detect them and to characterize them at

103
00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:22.380
a molecular level, and then to use that information to develop clinical

104
00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:25.960
approaches to target these cells to prevent recurrence.

105
00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:29.800
So one of the approaches that my laboratory has taken over the years to

106
00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:33.480
understanding dormancy biology is developing genetically

107
00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:37.320
engineered mouse models for human breast cancer that make

108
00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:40.890
use of the doxycycline-inducible, mammary-specific

109
00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:44.440
expression of oncogenes of interest in the mammary

110
00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:48.400
epithelium. And as shown here, when mice are put on doxycycline

111
00:06:48.440 --> 00:06:52.240
in their drinking water, in this case, they turn on the HER2 oncogene, and

112
00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:55.840
that drives the development of hyperplasias, and then

113
00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:59.240
ultimately invasive mammary adenocarcinomas that will

114
00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:02.920
metastasize. And as an example of oncogene

115
00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:03.560
addiction,

116
00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:08.640
with these mice with extant primary tumors, if

117
00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:11.100
doxycycline is removed from the drinking water,

118
00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:15.880
HER2 is then turned off in a tumor which has multiple

119
00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:19.510
mutations. These tumors rapidly regress to a

120
00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:22.820
non-palpable state over the course of several weeks,

121
00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:26.610
essentially a genetic approximation of targeted therapy.

122
00:07:27.340 --> 00:07:30.080
But if you follow these animals over time off

123
00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.420
doxycycline, just as in patients, tumors will

124
00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:37.420
recur stochastically and via a variety of

125
00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:41.170
escape pathways, and they really do it after a variable

126
00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:45.180
latency period. If you look at the site of a regressed

127
00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:48.860
primary tumor and genetically marked tumor cells, you can

128
00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:52.480
see that there is a collection of residual tumor cells

129
00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:56.720
that persists in these animals, which enables us to isolate them,

130
00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:01.060
query their biology, and try to understand the mechanisms of survival

131
00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:01.780
and recurrence.

132
00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:06.540
One important element if one follows the proliferation of these tumor cells,

133
00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:10.300
within three to five days after instituting this

134
00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:14.340
genetic targeted therapy, the proliferation rates

135
00:08:14.579 --> 00:08:18.360
crash, cells exit the cell cycle, and remain in this

136
00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:21.960
persistent quiescent state for many weeks,

137
00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:26.360
as shown here as well by BrdU labeling of

138
00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:30.080
these dormant residual lesions. But if you put animals back on

139
00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:33.980
doxycycline, turn the oncogene back on in those residual tumor

140
00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:38.040
cells, they rapidly reestablish proliferation rates

141
00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:41.740
and reenter the cell cycle. So they are genuinely reversibly

142
00:08:41.800 --> 00:08:44.720
quiescent or serially dormant.

143
00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:49.640
If we isolate these dormant RTCs, what we

144
00:08:49.700 --> 00:08:52.280
find is that they exist in a distinct cellular state.

145
00:08:52.420 --> 00:08:56.220
So dormant residual tumor cells are in a state that

146
00:08:56.260 --> 00:08:59.680
is different, both from the primary tumor cells from which they

147
00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:03.660
arose and the recurrent tumor cells to which they give rise.

148
00:09:03.950 --> 00:09:07.260
And this is true in multiple different animal models for

149
00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:11.160
dormancy and recurrence. And interestingly, across

150
00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:14.980
these different models, dormant RTCs share a

151
00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:17.280
variety of gene expression alterations.

152
00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.680
So what makes us think that this reflects anything relevant about human

153
00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:25.680
disease? Well, Amalya Sreekumar, who's in my lab

154
00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:29.660
and here speaking today, did very interesting work where she developed

155
00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:33.540
a core mouse dormancy signature from in vitro and in vivo

156
00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:36.920
mouse models of dormancy, and then applied it to

157
00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:40.780
neoadjuvant therapy breast cancer patient data sets

158
00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:45.040
in which there were initial biopsies of primary tumors pretreatment,

159
00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:49.120
and then surgical excision of the remaining residual lesions.

160
00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:52.900
And what she found in the majority of data sets

161
00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:57.180
is that there is an enrichment across multiple patient

162
00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:01.180
cohorts of this mouse core dormancy signature in

163
00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:04.120
the post-treatment samples from patients.

164
00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:08.580
And interestingly, this was independent of therapy, so seen both

165
00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:12.440
for endocrine therapy or chemotherapy, short or

166
00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:16.380
long. And this argues that therapy-refractory

167
00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.940
residual tumor cells that persist in patients

168
00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:23.940
following neoadjuvant therapy exhibit changes in gene

169
00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.500
expression that are similar to those associated with cellular

170
00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:30.940
dormancy in mice, arguing for at least some

171
00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:32.940
relevance of these models to the clinic.

172
00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:38.140
So using models such as this, we ask the question: can

173
00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:41.840
we identify dormancy-specific responses to therapy that we could

174
00:10:41.860 --> 00:10:45.240
leverage? Well, the inverse of that is, of course, chemotherapy,

175
00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:49.460
which effectively kills proliferating tumor cells but

176
00:10:49.540 --> 00:10:52.520
has very little effect on dormant tumor cells.

177
00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:56.540
So can we find the inverse of that? I'll show you one

178
00:10:56.580 --> 00:11:00.190
example of this to begin with. So this is Notch

179
00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:04.180
activation, looking at the Notch intracellular domain in dormant

180
00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:08.200
residual lesions in mice, showing that Notch is activated

181
00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:12.080
in maybe 40% of residual tumor cells in these mice,

182
00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:16.360
and we know this is Notch activation because it's blocked by the gamma secretase

183
00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:20.060
inhibitor. So we basically ask the question, if we inhibit Notch

184
00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:24.340
with a gamma secretase inhibitor at different stages of tumor progression,

185
00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:28.360
what happens? Well, if we inhibit Notch in

186
00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:32.180
animals as they're developing primary tumors, it has no

187
00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:34.380
effect on primary tumor genesis at all.

188
00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:39.170
If once animals have developed primary tumors, we treat them with Notch inhibitors,

189
00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:42.760
again, it has no effect at all. And if we treat

190
00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:46.440
animals with recurrent tumors, again, Notch

191
00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:50.300
inhibition has no effect, and if anything, accelerates recurrent

192
00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:52.900
tumor growth at the highest doses of GSI.

193
00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:57.080
But in contrast, if we treat animals bearing dormant

194
00:11:57.200 --> 00:12:00.940
residual disease with gamma secretase inhibitor, what we

195
00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:04.500
see is a pronounced improvement in

196
00:12:04.540 --> 00:12:08.060
recurrence-free survival in animals that is dose-dependent,

197
00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:12.280
where at the highest dose, about 50% of animals never

198
00:12:12.289 --> 00:12:15.860
recur at all. So this is clearly a dormancy-specific

199
00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:19.840
effect. So using approaches such as this, we've been attempting

200
00:12:19.850 --> 00:12:23.680
to catalog different pathways in which dormant

201
00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:26.880
residual tumor cells show a much greater

202
00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:30.722
dependency than proliferating tumor cells.As

203
00:12:30.832 --> 00:12:34.581
one example of this, as we thought ahead towards translation,

204
00:12:34.872 --> 00:12:38.792
was autophagy. So my lab and others have demonstrated

205
00:12:38.832 --> 00:12:42.672
that autophagy is activated in dormant tumor cells.

206
00:12:43.932 --> 00:12:47.712
And if one does an experiment in orthotopic

207
00:12:47.772 --> 00:12:51.752
tumor model in mice, in which we inactivate autophagy

208
00:12:51.812 --> 00:12:52.072
by

209
00:12:53.172 --> 00:12:57.052
knocking down either ATG5 or ATG7, which are required for

210
00:12:57.072 --> 00:13:00.972
autophagy, form primary tumors, allow them to regress to

211
00:13:01.072 --> 00:13:04.752
a dormant state, and simply ask: Is there a difference in rates of recurrence?

212
00:13:05.122 --> 00:13:09.012
And what we see is that in tumor cells in which autophagy has been

213
00:13:09.032 --> 00:13:12.752
disabled, there is a pronounced improvement in

214
00:13:12.792 --> 00:13:16.532
recurrence-free survival, arguing that autophagy is required for

215
00:13:16.572 --> 00:13:17.152
recurrence.

216
00:13:18.192 --> 00:13:21.812
If we do an isogenic competition assay

217
00:13:21.852 --> 00:13:25.832
between cells that have disabled autophagy or their isogenic

218
00:13:25.892 --> 00:13:29.832
controls, inject them at a one-to-one ratio into mice, form

219
00:13:29.912 --> 00:13:33.872
primary tumors, allow them to regress and then spontaneously recur.

220
00:13:34.491 --> 00:13:38.352
If we look at the ratio of those two cell types, what we see is

221
00:13:38.912 --> 00:13:40.072
that there is no

222
00:13:40.912 --> 00:13:44.572
proliferative-- there is no advantage or disadvantage for

223
00:13:44.592 --> 00:13:48.052
autophagy-deficient cells during primary tumor formation

224
00:13:48.472 --> 00:13:51.952
or initial tumor regression. But during the dormancy

225
00:13:52.072 --> 00:13:56.052
period, a difference appears in which cells in which

226
00:13:56.092 --> 00:13:56.912
autophagy

227
00:13:57.952 --> 00:14:01.132
has been impaired are at a selective

228
00:14:01.142 --> 00:14:04.672
disadvantage in animals. So autophagy appears to be

229
00:14:04.732 --> 00:14:07.552
required for the survival of dormant tumor cells.

230
00:14:07.582 --> 00:14:11.072
And consistent with this, if we pharmacologically block

231
00:14:11.112 --> 00:14:14.792
autophagy by administering chloroquine

232
00:14:15.332 --> 00:14:18.992
to mice bearing dormant residual disease and treat them for two

233
00:14:19.072 --> 00:14:22.912
weeks and simply count the number of residual tumor cells, we

234
00:14:22.992 --> 00:14:26.892
see a decrement in the number of surviving residual tumor

235
00:14:26.912 --> 00:14:30.872
cells in mice, arguing that chloroquine in the dormancy

236
00:14:30.912 --> 00:14:33.592
period will kill residual tumor cells.

237
00:14:34.472 --> 00:14:37.952
While administering chloroquine to animals bearing dormant

238
00:14:37.992 --> 00:14:41.472
disease chronically and then following them to a

239
00:14:41.532 --> 00:14:45.412
recurrence endpoint shows that autophagy inhibition

240
00:14:45.472 --> 00:14:48.612
by chloroquine results in an improvement in

241
00:14:48.692 --> 00:14:52.652
recurrence-free survival. And so the important element here

242
00:14:53.012 --> 00:14:56.952
is not just that chloroquine has an effect when given to animals

243
00:14:57.032 --> 00:15:00.692
bearing dormant residual disease, but that it really has no

244
00:15:00.732 --> 00:15:04.552
effect on primary tumor genesis or recurrent

245
00:15:05.012 --> 00:15:08.252
tumor growth. So these are dormancy-specific

246
00:15:08.332 --> 00:15:11.772
vulnerabilities. In a similar manner, mTOR

247
00:15:11.792 --> 00:15:13.992
inhibition, in this case by rapamycin,

248
00:15:14.892 --> 00:15:18.132
a brief period of rapamycin treatment to inhibit

249
00:15:18.252 --> 00:15:21.952
mTOR in mice bearing dormant disease reduces the number of

250
00:15:21.972 --> 00:15:25.892
residual tumor cells, and chronic treatment dramatically

251
00:15:25.912 --> 00:15:27.952
improves recurrence-free survival.

252
00:15:28.412 --> 00:15:29.052
And again,

253
00:15:29.872 --> 00:15:33.732
rapamycin inhibition of primary recurrent tumors has, at

254
00:15:33.812 --> 00:15:36.792
best, transient and modest effects, so

255
00:15:36.912 --> 00:15:38.452
dormancy-specific effects.

256
00:15:39.312 --> 00:15:42.892
So the lesson of 15 or 20 years of studies in

257
00:15:42.932 --> 00:15:46.692
mice has been essentially that any

258
00:15:46.812 --> 00:15:50.712
drug that will kill or reduce the number of

259
00:15:50.792 --> 00:15:54.612
dormant residual tumor cells ultimately reads

260
00:15:54.752 --> 00:15:58.712
out as an improvement in recurrence-free survival and suggests that

261
00:15:58.732 --> 00:16:02.292
dormancy, which is in some ways akin

262
00:16:02.332 --> 00:16:06.052
potentially to a surveillance period, is a window of

263
00:16:06.092 --> 00:16:09.562
therapeutic vulnerability that may not exist in other phases.

264
00:16:09.952 --> 00:16:13.872
And so we sought to take advantage of these observations to

265
00:16:13.932 --> 00:16:14.812
translate this.

266
00:16:15.832 --> 00:16:19.772
We did this through the CLEVER therapeutic trials supported by a

267
00:16:19.832 --> 00:16:23.212
joint R01 with my close collaborator, Angie DeMichele.

268
00:16:24.192 --> 00:16:28.012
And essentially, these were concurrent parallel mouse and

269
00:16:28.072 --> 00:16:31.792
human trials targeting residual tumor cells in the

270
00:16:31.832 --> 00:16:35.012
surveillance phase. The targeted pathways were

271
00:16:35.412 --> 00:16:39.312
autophagy, mTOR signaling, or their combination, and there was a

272
00:16:39.352 --> 00:16:43.192
mouse preclinical trial and then a parallel patient trial.

273
00:16:44.292 --> 00:16:48.192
So the mouse CLEVER preclinical trial tested transient

274
00:16:48.212 --> 00:16:50.572
therapy and combination therapy.

275
00:16:50.612 --> 00:16:54.282
So we started with mice that harbored dormant residual tumor cells,

276
00:16:54.772 --> 00:16:58.572
and we treated them for either three weeks, nine weeks, or

277
00:16:58.672 --> 00:17:02.292
chronically with either rapamycin or

278
00:17:02.352 --> 00:17:05.272
everolimus to block mTOR, chloroquine or

279
00:17:05.312 --> 00:17:09.152
hydroxychloroquine to block autophagy, or the combination of

280
00:17:09.232 --> 00:17:11.692
everolimus and hydroxychloroquine.

281
00:17:11.772 --> 00:17:15.452
And we used a recurrence-free survival as an endpoint.

282
00:17:16.072 --> 00:17:19.883
And what we saw is shown here for everolimus is that this

283
00:17:19.952 --> 00:17:23.853
is the recurrence rate of untreated controls.

284
00:17:24.712 --> 00:17:28.632
This is chronically treated animals with everolimus

285
00:17:28.642 --> 00:17:31.892
showing this dramatic prolongation in recurrence-free survival.

286
00:17:32.272 --> 00:17:35.772
But animals treated transiently for three or nine weeks with

287
00:17:35.832 --> 00:17:39.812
everolimus also showed a marked improvement in recurrence-free

288
00:17:39.872 --> 00:17:43.752
survival. We saw a similar pattern, albeit more modest,

289
00:17:44.152 --> 00:17:47.652
with treatment for hydroxychloroquine or chloroquine.

290
00:17:48.072 --> 00:17:51.032
And I will say the combination of everolimus and

291
00:17:51.052 --> 00:17:54.352
hydroxychloroquine was at most modestly

292
00:17:54.472 --> 00:17:58.112
better than everolimus alone. So that was the recurrence-free

293
00:17:58.192 --> 00:18:01.992
survival endpoint. If we digitally counted the

294
00:18:02.052 --> 00:18:05.912
number of surviving residual tumor cells in these animals at the three-week and

295
00:18:05.952 --> 00:18:09.512
nine-week periods, what we found was that, again, mTOR

296
00:18:09.552 --> 00:18:12.792
inhibition or autophagy inhibition led to a

297
00:18:12.852 --> 00:18:16.372
decrement in the number of residual tumor cells, with

298
00:18:16.452 --> 00:18:19.992
mTOR inhibition showing the greatest effects.

299
00:18:20.132 --> 00:18:21.472
And interestingly,

300
00:18:22.492 --> 00:18:25.912
as we looked at the association between

301
00:18:26.032 --> 00:18:29.892
RTC burden and recurrence-free survival, what we found

302
00:18:29.952 --> 00:18:33.728
is thatThe greater the extent to which we depleted

303
00:18:33.768 --> 00:18:37.388
residual tumor cells, the greater the improvement in

304
00:18:37.428 --> 00:18:40.128
recurrence-free survival, and this

305
00:18:40.668 --> 00:18:44.588
regression actually has quite an impressive R squared

306
00:18:44.688 --> 00:18:46.248
value. So the extent

307
00:18:47.248 --> 00:18:50.968
of residual tumor cell depletion is highly correlated with the

308
00:18:50.978 --> 00:18:53.748
extent of improvement in recurrence-free survival.

309
00:18:54.868 --> 00:18:58.628
So that was the mouse trial. The phase two CLEVER

310
00:18:59.028 --> 00:19:03.018
patient trial for recurrence prevention had the major goals,

311
00:19:03.148 --> 00:19:07.068
first of feasibility and safety, since I can't tell you how many

312
00:19:07.168 --> 00:19:10.688
times we were told this is an impossible trial to do.

313
00:19:10.828 --> 00:19:13.028
No one will do it, no one will fund it.

314
00:19:13.388 --> 00:19:16.608
And this is really can one do a DTC-targeted

315
00:19:16.618 --> 00:19:18.708
trial in the surveillance window?

316
00:19:19.948 --> 00:19:23.428
The ancillary goal was, well, can a targeted intervention

317
00:19:23.508 --> 00:19:26.108
actually measurably decrease DTC burden?

318
00:19:27.068 --> 00:19:30.768
As an exploratory endpoint, are there any alterations of recurrence-free

319
00:19:30.788 --> 00:19:34.568
survival? And then long-term follow-up and repeated testing of

320
00:19:35.028 --> 00:19:38.348
these patients, and this trial was supported by this joint R01,

321
00:19:38.848 --> 00:19:42.788
major contributions from the Abramson Cancer Center through the To Prevent

322
00:19:42.888 --> 00:19:44.368
Translational Center of Excellence.

323
00:19:45.288 --> 00:19:46.848
So in the CLEVER trial,

324
00:19:47.748 --> 00:19:51.648
again, a phase two trial, eligible patients would've been diagnosed within

325
00:19:51.728 --> 00:19:52.528
five years

326
00:19:53.528 --> 00:19:56.748
of the study entry and had completed definitive treatment

327
00:19:57.108 --> 00:20:00.888
except for endocrine therapy, and had to have one of the following, either

328
00:20:00.948 --> 00:20:04.868
triple-negative disease, HER2 or ER-positive

329
00:20:04.928 --> 00:20:08.648
disease with positive lymph nodes or residual disease

330
00:20:08.708 --> 00:20:12.168
after neoadjuvant therapy, or ER positive

331
00:20:12.228 --> 00:20:15.808
disease with an oncotype score greater than

332
00:20:15.968 --> 00:20:19.148
25 or a high risk of MammaPrint test.

333
00:20:20.368 --> 00:20:24.068
So these are all, of course, standard markers for high risk of

334
00:20:24.088 --> 00:20:28.048
recurrence. And then in addition, a patient had to be willing to undergo

335
00:20:28.068 --> 00:20:31.568
a bone marrow aspirate. For those patients who were,

336
00:20:32.068 --> 00:20:36.028
there was a screening bone marrow aspirate on the SURMOUNT screening study

337
00:20:36.108 --> 00:20:40.048
run by Dr. Demichelle. These aspirates

338
00:20:40.068 --> 00:20:43.928
were screened by immunohistochemistry using a pan cytokeratin

339
00:20:43.968 --> 00:20:47.948
antibody, so a well-worked-out biomarker for DTCs.

340
00:20:48.488 --> 00:20:52.328
And those DTC positive patients were randomized

341
00:20:52.388 --> 00:20:55.508
to one of four treatment arms. Six cycles of

342
00:20:55.548 --> 00:20:59.108
hydroxychloroquine alone, everolimus alone,

343
00:20:59.508 --> 00:21:03.258
or their combination, and then a fourth arm who were

344
00:21:03.328 --> 00:21:06.748
observed for three months, and then at the end of that three-month

345
00:21:06.788 --> 00:21:10.778
period, they were given six cycles of hydroxychloroquine and

346
00:21:10.848 --> 00:21:14.708
everolimus. Patients were monitored by

347
00:21:14.748 --> 00:21:18.478
bone marrow aspirates at three-month intervals, and after six cycles,

348
00:21:18.908 --> 00:21:22.548
patients who were still DTC positive were offered an

349
00:21:22.608 --> 00:21:25.888
additional six cycles of combination therapy.

350
00:21:26.968 --> 00:21:29.748
In all, 51 patients received study treatment.

351
00:21:30.428 --> 00:21:32.968
All arms met the criteria for feasibility.

352
00:21:33.438 --> 00:21:37.388
There were no unexpected adverse events, and there was no grade

353
00:21:37.428 --> 00:21:41.308
four or five toxicity. So it was clearly a feasible trial.

354
00:21:42.328 --> 00:21:46.248
So what were the other results? If we looked at treatment effects on

355
00:21:46.288 --> 00:21:49.848
DTCs as assessed by this immunohistochemistry

356
00:21:49.988 --> 00:21:53.908
endpoint, after three cycles of either

357
00:21:53.948 --> 00:21:57.328
hydroxychloroquine alone, everolimus alone or their combination,

358
00:21:58.968 --> 00:22:02.448
the DTC number was significantly reduced

359
00:22:02.748 --> 00:22:06.228
compared to the observation arm, with reductions in

360
00:22:06.328 --> 00:22:09.728
DTC burden of about 80% and a

361
00:22:09.788 --> 00:22:13.728
corresponding increase in the fraction of patients who did not have

362
00:22:13.768 --> 00:22:17.368
detectable DTCs using the IHC assay.

363
00:22:18.288 --> 00:22:21.858
For recurrence-free survival, which is of course an exploratory

364
00:22:21.888 --> 00:22:25.608
endpoint since we're not powered for that, after a median follow-up of

365
00:22:25.808 --> 00:22:29.288
77 months, five-year recurrence-free survival across all

366
00:22:29.328 --> 00:22:33.228
groups was about 96%, which is substantially

367
00:22:33.248 --> 00:22:36.848
better than would be expected based on the high-risk nature of this

368
00:22:36.868 --> 00:22:40.628
population, and there's at least the suggestion that

369
00:22:40.638 --> 00:22:44.248
patients who cleared their DTCs, air quotes around

370
00:22:44.368 --> 00:22:48.018
cleared, they may have better outcomes, recurrence outcomes,

371
00:22:48.408 --> 00:22:51.748
than those who do not. But too early to tell.

372
00:22:52.548 --> 00:22:56.308
So the lessons of the CLEVER trials was first, we see concordant

373
00:22:56.348 --> 00:23:00.128
effects in patients than in mice, which gives us greater confidence in the

374
00:23:00.148 --> 00:23:01.908
predictive ability of these models.

375
00:23:02.788 --> 00:23:06.228
Transient inhibition of autophagy or mTOR during this

376
00:23:06.328 --> 00:23:10.188
surveillance period can both reduce RTC burden

377
00:23:10.688 --> 00:23:14.287
and, at least in mice and perhaps in patients, improve

378
00:23:14.348 --> 00:23:15.448
recurrence-free survival.

379
00:23:16.268 --> 00:23:20.008
Effects on RTC number and recurrence-free survival are

380
00:23:20.068 --> 00:23:23.688
correlated, suggesting that RTC burden may

381
00:23:23.728 --> 00:23:27.148
be a useful surrogate endpoint biomarker for recurrence.

382
00:23:27.488 --> 00:23:31.248
But I think most importantly, this is proof of concept, that a

383
00:23:31.328 --> 00:23:31.888
transient

384
00:23:32.728 --> 00:23:36.398
mechanism-based pharmacological intervention that's

385
00:23:36.488 --> 00:23:40.028
aimed at residual tumor cells may be a

386
00:23:40.128 --> 00:23:43.768
feasible approach to prevent recurrence, and there are

387
00:23:43.828 --> 00:23:47.588
follow-on trials being conducted by Dr.

388
00:23:47.648 --> 00:23:50.528
Demichelle and other investigators at our institution as well.

389
00:23:51.368 --> 00:23:55.248
Well, one of the things that became evident during the CLEVER trial was really

390
00:23:55.258 --> 00:23:59.188
a tremendous need for improved DTC biomarker development.

391
00:23:59.488 --> 00:24:03.348
And this really arises from a number of limitations of the

392
00:24:03.388 --> 00:24:07.227
immunohistochemistry test. So it's low throughput, it's low

393
00:24:07.348 --> 00:24:11.168
sensitivity. If you look at something that is a DTC

394
00:24:11.508 --> 00:24:15.288
versus something that the pathologist says is not a DTC, it's

395
00:24:15.348 --> 00:24:19.288
clear you need a pathologist who's trained in order to read these studies.

396
00:24:20.228 --> 00:24:23.998
There's also, I would say, a general dearth of information on the

397
00:24:24.108 --> 00:24:28.038
test characteristics of this, particularly sensitivity and

398
00:24:28.168 --> 00:24:31.892
specificity.And because it lacks

399
00:24:31.952 --> 00:24:35.492
sensitivity, there's a high false negative rate from

400
00:24:35.652 --> 00:24:39.252
studying just one bone marrow aspirate, since the most common

401
00:24:39.312 --> 00:24:42.812
result of this assay is either you detect zero

402
00:24:42.832 --> 00:24:46.812
DTCs or one DTC. And then, of course,

403
00:24:46.872 --> 00:24:50.832
since all you're getting here is a brown cell or not, you

404
00:24:50.852 --> 00:24:53.832
have no information on the biological properties of these cells.

405
00:24:54.572 --> 00:24:58.372
So it was apparent that there's a need for other tests,

406
00:24:58.702 --> 00:25:01.142
and there are many approaches to this. I'll tell you about one.

407
00:25:01.591 --> 00:25:04.952
But the need for increased sensitivity and dynamic range of a test,

408
00:25:05.622 --> 00:25:08.962
the hope of finding a valid surrogate

409
00:25:09.072 --> 00:25:12.912
biomarker to first accurately identify patients who have

410
00:25:12.952 --> 00:25:16.152
DTCs, and are therefore at elevated risk, to

411
00:25:16.232 --> 00:25:20.172
quantify their burden, to molecularly characterize

412
00:25:20.182 --> 00:25:23.632
their cells, to be able to assess their risk of

413
00:25:23.672 --> 00:25:27.392
reactivation and recurrence, and to be able to measure the effects of

414
00:25:27.432 --> 00:25:30.772
therapy targeting DTCs in real time.

415
00:25:31.142 --> 00:25:34.332
And perhaps the ultimate hope of being able to phenotype

416
00:25:34.392 --> 00:25:38.342
DTCs to be able to match the right therapy to the right

417
00:25:38.342 --> 00:25:42.052
patient based on the particular flavor of DTCs they might

418
00:25:42.132 --> 00:25:45.932
have. So we turn to flow cytometry as an approach for

419
00:25:46.012 --> 00:25:49.962
this, using markers EpCAM and

420
00:25:50.012 --> 00:25:53.452
HER2, as shown here in tumor cell spiking

421
00:25:53.532 --> 00:25:57.112
studies into normal donor bone marrows.

422
00:25:57.472 --> 00:26:01.092
We first depleted bone marrows of CD45 positive cells,

423
00:26:01.892 --> 00:26:02.372
and then,

424
00:26:03.232 --> 00:26:06.832
using HER2 and EpCAM, as well as CD45, stained them

425
00:26:07.352 --> 00:26:11.112
where we can detect DTCs compared

426
00:26:11.192 --> 00:26:15.092
to what are largely CD45 negative normal

427
00:26:15.172 --> 00:26:17.352
bone marrow cells in the shaded region.

428
00:26:17.892 --> 00:26:21.772
We can detect DTCs here shown down to a one in one

429
00:26:21.852 --> 00:26:25.712
million spiking frequency, but looked at over a

430
00:26:25.832 --> 00:26:29.732
wide range of dilutions, we can detect down to about

431
00:26:29.812 --> 00:26:33.622
one tumor cell in 10 million normal bone marrow cells,

432
00:26:33.932 --> 00:26:36.272
and the assay is highly linear.

433
00:26:37.731 --> 00:26:41.092
We can use this to detect DTC populations,

434
00:26:41.712 --> 00:26:45.272
here shown in metastatic patients who have substantial

435
00:26:45.372 --> 00:26:49.091
numbers of DTCs per mil of bone marrow aspirate.

436
00:26:49.812 --> 00:26:53.692
And then in early stage breast cancer patients as well,

437
00:26:53.812 --> 00:26:56.972
as shown by the much smaller number of cells

438
00:26:57.652 --> 00:26:58.392
shown here,

439
00:26:59.492 --> 00:27:03.232
here, and here, where we can see a

440
00:27:03.292 --> 00:27:07.262
range of phenotypes from cells that are HER2 positive, and I'll

441
00:27:07.352 --> 00:27:10.952
just say this is HER2 expressing, not HER2 amplified,

442
00:27:11.672 --> 00:27:15.152
EpCAM expressing, but not HER2, or some double

443
00:27:15.292 --> 00:27:19.112
positive cells. So we can detect these cells both in

444
00:27:19.152 --> 00:27:20.992
metastatic and early stage patients.

445
00:27:21.832 --> 00:27:25.132
If we visualize these cells using, in this case,

446
00:27:25.232 --> 00:27:29.212
ImageStream, we can see here, sort of using human

447
00:27:29.272 --> 00:27:31.272
breast cancer cell lines as an example,

448
00:27:32.152 --> 00:27:35.952
that claudin-low breast cancer cell lines tend to

449
00:27:36.012 --> 00:27:39.832
become EpCAM negative, but they still express some HER2,

450
00:27:40.352 --> 00:27:43.952
much lower than the amounts expressed in HER2 amplified cells.

451
00:27:44.312 --> 00:27:47.652
But garden variety DTCs frequently are EpCAM

452
00:27:47.732 --> 00:27:50.822
positive, HER2 positive at this lower

453
00:27:51.192 --> 00:27:55.132
endogenous level, and of course pancytokeratin positive.

454
00:27:55.852 --> 00:27:59.372
In some patients, we see that bone marrow DTCs become

455
00:27:59.412 --> 00:28:03.132
cytokeratin negative, EpCAM negative, but will still

456
00:28:03.192 --> 00:28:06.812
express HER2 above background levels, even in

457
00:28:06.872 --> 00:28:10.292
patients whose metastases have a mixture of cells

458
00:28:10.352 --> 00:28:13.632
expressing or not expressing cytokeratins or EpCAM.

459
00:28:13.712 --> 00:28:17.642
So staining for HER2 enables the detection of

460
00:28:17.672 --> 00:28:20.212
these claudin-low human breast cancer cells.

461
00:28:21.192 --> 00:28:25.132
If we do Smart-seq2 expression profiling of patient

462
00:28:25.192 --> 00:28:29.002
DTCs, and I'll just say we're at the very beginning of these sorts of studies,

463
00:28:29.532 --> 00:28:33.132
what we see is clusters of different human breast cancer cell lines,

464
00:28:34.032 --> 00:28:37.872
normal. These are CD45 positive normal human

465
00:28:37.952 --> 00:28:40.952
bone marrow cells. And then three distinct

466
00:28:41.012 --> 00:28:44.752
clusters of DTCs isolated from early stage breast

467
00:28:44.792 --> 00:28:48.741
cancer patients that have distinct expression profiles.

468
00:28:49.472 --> 00:28:53.112
In terms of physical properties, compared to human breast cancer cell

469
00:28:53.172 --> 00:28:56.631
lines in terms of size, estimated by forward scatter,

470
00:28:57.152 --> 00:29:00.892
that DTCs are smaller than human breast

471
00:29:00.952 --> 00:29:04.792
cancer cell lines growing in culture, but somewhat larger than

472
00:29:04.832 --> 00:29:05.492
different

473
00:29:06.392 --> 00:29:08.912
white blood cell types present in bone marrow.

474
00:29:09.342 --> 00:29:13.052
And similarly, their complexity is intermediate between breast

475
00:29:13.112 --> 00:29:16.532
cancer cell lines and at least monocytes and lymphocytes.

476
00:29:16.572 --> 00:29:18.612
So distinct physical properties.

477
00:29:19.272 --> 00:29:22.932
As you might predict based on levels of proliferation

478
00:29:23.012 --> 00:29:26.312
markers compared to human breast cancer cell lines,

479
00:29:27.092 --> 00:29:31.032
DTCs tend to express relatively low levels of proliferation

480
00:29:31.112 --> 00:29:34.172
markers. And then looked at more broadly,

481
00:29:34.992 --> 00:29:38.392
if we do hierarchical clustering, we see our breast cancer cell

482
00:29:38.412 --> 00:29:40.832
lines isolated at a single cell level,

483
00:29:42.512 --> 00:29:46.462
separate from our disseminated tumor cell clusters and

484
00:29:46.532 --> 00:29:50.382
normal bone marrow controls. Here are the three DTC clusters.

485
00:29:50.792 --> 00:29:53.912
Here are the different human breast cancer cell lines.

486
00:29:53.972 --> 00:29:57.262
We can detect mutations and copy number alterations,

487
00:29:57.352 --> 00:30:00.532
really across the DTCs and the human cell lines.

488
00:30:01.072 --> 00:30:05.032
Mutations somewhat less robustly, I will say, but this is

489
00:30:05.112 --> 00:30:08.532
in contrast, of course, to normal human bone marrow controls.

490
00:30:09.032 --> 00:30:12.852
And if we look at our DTC clusters, we see two of the

491
00:30:12.892 --> 00:30:16.172
clusters are luminal with estrogen response

492
00:30:16.232 --> 00:30:20.152
signatures, as well as some expression of ERBB2

493
00:30:20.212 --> 00:30:24.012
that is lower than that in amplified cells, proliferation

494
00:30:24.132 --> 00:30:27.631
low, as I said. And then our third

495
00:30:27.732 --> 00:30:31.684
clusterAppears to be more mesenchymal, to have

496
00:30:31.724 --> 00:30:35.604
a basal greater than luminal set of markers, and a

497
00:30:35.684 --> 00:30:39.124
lower estrogen response. So clearly different

498
00:30:39.184 --> 00:30:43.084
flavors of patient DTCs. And then finally, I will just

499
00:30:43.144 --> 00:30:46.564
say that if one analyzes the genomics of these cells,

500
00:30:47.004 --> 00:30:50.664
that DTCs commonly share driver mutations

501
00:30:50.964 --> 00:30:54.424
that were present in the primary tumor with some additions,

502
00:30:54.644 --> 00:30:56.584
perhaps, at least the suggestion of that.

503
00:30:57.244 --> 00:30:59.464
And bone marrow DTCs

504
00:31:00.564 --> 00:31:04.444
share, of course, driver mutations with the metastases to which they

505
00:31:04.504 --> 00:31:08.044
gave rise, but may be missing key driver

506
00:31:08.084 --> 00:31:11.944
mutations that arose later on. So in this case, a patient treated

507
00:31:11.984 --> 00:31:15.464
with an aromatase inhibitor who developed an estrogen receptor

508
00:31:15.544 --> 00:31:19.134
mutation in the metastatic tumor that we did not detect in the

509
00:31:19.144 --> 00:31:22.904
DTCs that we analyzed. So on at least the suggestion of

510
00:31:23.004 --> 00:31:26.124
ongoing genomic evolution. So in conclusion,

511
00:31:26.564 --> 00:31:30.364
dormancy is a unique window of susceptibility to

512
00:31:30.444 --> 00:31:30.924
therapy.

513
00:31:31.804 --> 00:31:35.564
Treatments that reduce DTC burden when given during this surveillance

514
00:31:35.684 --> 00:31:38.784
period appear to prevent recurrence or at least have that potential.

515
00:31:39.514 --> 00:31:43.504
That intervention in this surveillance period does appear to be feasible

516
00:31:43.544 --> 00:31:45.004
and may have clinical utility.

517
00:31:45.984 --> 00:31:49.924
Having a better test is essential, and then really the ultimate goal is to

518
00:31:49.964 --> 00:31:53.244
change the paradigm. Who is it that needs therapy?

519
00:31:53.604 --> 00:31:57.484
That is, who are the people who actually have residual disease, and

520
00:31:57.524 --> 00:32:01.044
can you spare the people further therapy who do not have

521
00:32:01.064 --> 00:32:02.584
detectable residual disease?

522
00:32:03.644 --> 00:32:05.384
What kind of therapy should be given?

523
00:32:05.764 --> 00:32:07.924
Well, I think the direction should be analyzing

524
00:32:08.744 --> 00:32:12.684
unique dependencies of dormant tumor cells. Which therapy?

525
00:32:12.784 --> 00:32:16.564
Well, the best thing would be to select therapies based on the properties of

526
00:32:16.624 --> 00:32:20.084
those cells. And then finally, did the therapy work?

527
00:32:20.454 --> 00:32:23.644
The ability to do real-time pharmacodynamic

528
00:32:23.684 --> 00:32:27.644
monitoring of patients treated with DTC targeting therapies.

529
00:32:27.664 --> 00:32:31.564
And ultimately putting these things together, I think raises the hope

530
00:32:31.964 --> 00:32:35.384
for the ability to prevent breast cancer recurrence by targeting

531
00:32:35.424 --> 00:32:38.664
DTCs as well as its associated mortality.

