00:37:48.648 --> 00:37:49.148
Award.

624
00:37:50.188 --> 00:37:54.168
I'm really excited to talk to you about this study that really, when we

625
00:37:54.228 --> 00:37:57.668
first saw it, took us by surprise, and challenged our

626
00:37:57.708 --> 00:38:01.408
notion of mammary lineage fidelity during breast

627
00:38:01.448 --> 00:38:02.467
cancer progression.

628
00:38:03.648 --> 00:38:06.648
The title of my talk is Residual Breast Cancer Cells Co-opt

629
00:38:06.748 --> 00:38:10.048
SOX5-driven Endochondral Ossification to Maintain

630
00:38:10.108 --> 00:38:10.828
Dormancy.

631
00:38:13.048 --> 00:38:14.748
As Lewis already introduced,

632
00:38:15.748 --> 00:38:19.288
the key question driving the clinical finding that's driving the

633
00:38:19.348 --> 00:38:23.068
research that we do in the lab is that breast cancer is the leading cause of

634
00:38:23.128 --> 00:38:26.368
cancer-related deaths in women worldwide.

635
00:38:26.428 --> 00:38:30.248
So advanced diagnostics as well as targeted therapies have rendered the

636
00:38:30.288 --> 00:38:34.268
primary tumors highly curable. But in about 30% of

637
00:38:34.348 --> 00:38:37.728
patients, these tumors come back after several years or

638
00:38:37.738 --> 00:38:41.698
decades and are incurable, and account for the vast majority

639
00:38:41.768 --> 00:38:44.628
of mortality that's associated with this disease.

640
00:38:46.508 --> 00:38:50.448
So this is plotted here as tumor burden over time, where you can see

641
00:38:50.568 --> 00:38:54.088
this long clinical latency window following definitive

642
00:38:54.188 --> 00:38:57.968
treatment of the primary tumor and prior to relapse,

643
00:38:58.528 --> 00:39:02.168
which necessitates a better understanding of the biology underlying

644
00:39:02.208 --> 00:39:04.448
minimal residual disease, as seen here.

645
00:39:06.248 --> 00:39:10.028
More specifically, what I mean by that is the residual

646
00:39:10.068 --> 00:39:13.768
tumor cells, or RTCs, as I'll refer to them, that make up

647
00:39:13.868 --> 00:39:17.728
MRD. If we could understand the biology by which they

648
00:39:17.768 --> 00:39:21.748
persist, survive, and ultimately give rise to recurrences, we

649
00:39:21.808 --> 00:39:25.648
could devise ways to either eliminate them or prevent their outgrowth

650
00:39:25.748 --> 00:39:28.128
in order to improve patient outcomes.

651
00:39:30.228 --> 00:39:34.168
So one of the emerging hypotheses that's attractive and is

652
00:39:34.468 --> 00:39:38.068
showing up from existing data is that the selective pressures

653
00:39:38.528 --> 00:39:42.408
such as therapy and metastasis might induce a bottleneck

654
00:39:42.488 --> 00:39:46.288
that results in convergent phenotypes on

655
00:39:46.328 --> 00:39:50.068
these RTCs, as you can see here. And what I mean by that

656
00:39:50.268 --> 00:39:53.388
is that maybe there is the possibility

657
00:39:53.948 --> 00:39:57.888
that RTCs converge upon phenotypes that are independent of

658
00:39:57.928 --> 00:40:01.748
the specific stressor that caused them to achieve that state.

659
00:40:03.808 --> 00:40:07.328
One such adaptive mechanism that's been observed is the

660
00:40:07.388 --> 00:40:11.148
acquisition of a reversible state of non-proliferation by

661
00:40:11.208 --> 00:40:13.388
these RTCs that we term dormancy.

662
00:40:14.528 --> 00:40:17.908
So this has actually been observed in patients where RTCs

663
00:40:18.908 --> 00:40:22.428
are observed following both therapy as well as

664
00:40:22.448 --> 00:40:26.328
metastasis, and are thought to be reversibly quiescent such that they

665
00:40:26.388 --> 00:40:29.588
can give rise to recurrences after a long period of time.

666
00:40:30.188 --> 00:40:34.168
So this also constitutes an attractive model for why these cells

667
00:40:34.208 --> 00:40:38.048
persist for long periods of time in the latency window

668
00:40:38.108 --> 00:40:39.368
prior to recurrence.

669
00:40:41.108 --> 00:40:44.528
So Lewis already introduced the genetically engineered mouse models that were

670
00:40:44.548 --> 00:40:48.168
developed in his lab that I was using to identify

671
00:40:48.228 --> 00:40:52.177
mechanisms by which RTCs selectively survive and give rise to

672
00:40:52.228 --> 00:40:55.948
recurrence. Just as a reminder, the model that I'll be focusing

673
00:40:56.128 --> 00:40:59.207
on is this MtbTan model, where you can use

674
00:40:59.228 --> 00:41:02.788
doxycycline to toggle oncogenes on or off in the mammary

675
00:41:02.808 --> 00:41:06.088
epithelium, in this case, of the HER2 oncogene.

676
00:41:06.668 --> 00:41:10.628
So in the presence of dox, HER2 drives primary tumor formation,

677
00:41:11.088 --> 00:41:14.588
and withdrawal of dox causes its regression to a non-palpable

678
00:41:14.597 --> 00:41:18.168
state. And after an extended period of time, these tumors

679
00:41:18.228 --> 00:41:21.988
recur in a manner that's independent of that HER2 driver

680
00:41:22.048 --> 00:41:22.608
oncogene.

681
00:41:25.068 --> 00:41:28.728
So using the cells derived from this MtbTan model, I

682
00:41:29.688 --> 00:41:33.288
created a Cas9 constitutive expressing version of these cell

683
00:41:33.348 --> 00:41:37.148
lines and used that for a targeted CRISPR-Cas9

684
00:41:37.268 --> 00:41:41.048
screen to identify mechanisms that drive RTC

685
00:41:41.108 --> 00:41:44.628
survival as well as their subsequent recurrence.

686
00:41:45.288 --> 00:41:49.188
To do so, we designed a guide RNA library targeting genes that

687
00:41:49.228 --> 00:41:53.208
are selectively enriched in dormant time points relative to their

688
00:41:53.248 --> 00:41:56.768
proliferative counterparts. And this resulted in a guide RNA

689
00:41:56.848 --> 00:42:00.608
library of about 500 guide RNAs that we transduced

690
00:42:00.688 --> 00:42:04.308
into this Cas9 expressing cell line at a low

691
00:42:04.348 --> 00:42:08.168
multiplicity of infection to ensure a single guide RNA

692
00:42:08.208 --> 00:42:11.708
per cell. What we can do with that is that the

693
00:42:11.768 --> 00:42:15.438
presence or the abundance of guide RNAs can serve as a proxy for cell

694
00:42:15.488 --> 00:42:19.088
numbers. So after injection into mice, we

695
00:42:19.148 --> 00:42:23.048
harvested primary tumors, multiple residual lesion time points

696
00:42:23.108 --> 00:42:26.768
at both early and late stages, as well as recurrent tumors,

697
00:42:27.208 --> 00:42:31.148
and performed next gen sequencing to identify guide RNA abundance at each

698
00:42:31.208 --> 00:42:32.268
of these time points.

699
00:42:34.408 --> 00:42:38.128
So the first project that resulted from this was actually published a few

700
00:42:38.208 --> 00:42:42.168
years ago and identified the enrichment of a

701
00:42:42.288 --> 00:42:45.608
sugar-modified molecule called proteoglycan as being

702
00:42:45.708 --> 00:42:49.248
selectively enriched and required for dormant

703
00:42:49.348 --> 00:42:50.508
RTC survival

704
00:42:51.648 --> 00:42:55.322
early during this process.For the study that I'll

705
00:42:55.332 --> 00:42:58.372
describe today, we were interested in asking what are the

706
00:42:58.412 --> 00:43:02.162
mechanisms enabling these RTCs to persist in a

707
00:43:02.232 --> 00:43:06.122
dormant state, for which we focused on the latter half of the screen and

708
00:43:06.232 --> 00:43:09.772
looked for clonal enrichment at these later stage time

709
00:43:09.872 --> 00:43:10.352
points.

710
00:43:13.372 --> 00:43:17.112
So I mentioned that we had a library of about 500 guide

711
00:43:17.212 --> 00:43:21.192
RNAs, so the expected guide RNA abundance per guide

712
00:43:21.252 --> 00:43:24.892
in this pool is 0.2%. To call a

713
00:43:24.912 --> 00:43:28.772
clonally enriching guide RNA, we used a threshold of

714
00:43:29.032 --> 00:43:32.592
5%, which is about 25-fold higher than

715
00:43:32.672 --> 00:43:36.112
this existing baseline abundance.

716
00:43:37.832 --> 00:43:41.592
And we looked for abundance that's increasing at these late stage

717
00:43:41.672 --> 00:43:44.992
time points in late residual lesions as well as

718
00:43:45.052 --> 00:43:45.932
recurrences.

719
00:43:47.592 --> 00:43:51.552
These data are depicted here in stack bar plots, and what you're looking at

720
00:43:51.712 --> 00:43:55.232
is the abundance of the top 10 guide RNAs in each of these

721
00:43:55.312 --> 00:43:59.111
samples boxed by time points. And looking

722
00:43:59.192 --> 00:44:02.992
across this, you can already tell that there is a stochastic enrichment of

723
00:44:03.072 --> 00:44:05.252
guides as you go through this time course.

724
00:44:06.352 --> 00:44:07.532
To sort of

725
00:44:08.992 --> 00:44:12.872
strengthen our confidence in the guide RNAs that

726
00:44:12.952 --> 00:44:16.922
we identify using this approach, we additionally looked for guides that

727
00:44:16.972 --> 00:44:20.892
were enriched in two or more samples, which is represented by the

728
00:44:20.952 --> 00:44:21.792
colored bars.

729
00:44:24.052 --> 00:44:27.712
And of these hits, SOX5, which is indicated

730
00:44:27.772 --> 00:44:31.332
here in samples that had enrichment by the red arrows,

731
00:44:32.252 --> 00:44:36.172
demonstrated enrichment in multiple samples as well as

732
00:44:36.212 --> 00:44:39.972
with multiple guide RNAs. So we proceeded with validating SOX5

733
00:44:40.052 --> 00:44:41.892
as one of our top hits from the screen.

734
00:44:44.432 --> 00:44:48.372
So to do so, we first performed a recurrence-free survival assay where

735
00:44:48.472 --> 00:44:52.012
we introduced cells containing either the guide

736
00:44:52.092 --> 00:44:56.012
RNA targeting the inner Trosa locus or one targeting

737
00:44:56.092 --> 00:44:59.012
SOX5 that we identified from the screen

738
00:44:59.452 --> 00:45:03.372
orthotopically injected into the inguinal fat pad in the mammary

739
00:45:03.432 --> 00:45:07.252
gland here, and waited for spontaneous recurrences after

740
00:45:07.312 --> 00:45:08.772
Her2 downregulation.

741
00:45:09.712 --> 00:45:13.692
So the clonal enrichment we observed from the screen predicted to

742
00:45:13.772 --> 00:45:17.612
us that likely loss of SOX5 would result in an

743
00:45:17.672 --> 00:45:21.472
acceleration of recurrence, which is actually what we see here

744
00:45:21.532 --> 00:45:25.192
with two independent guide RNAs targeting SOX5 that we identified in the

745
00:45:25.272 --> 00:45:29.212
screen. You see this acceleration of recurrence indicated with these

746
00:45:29.272 --> 00:45:32.032
hazard ratios of about 2.5 to three.

747
00:45:34.612 --> 00:45:38.352
We next wanted to ask if this was also true in a non-orthotopic

748
00:45:38.432 --> 00:45:42.012
site. So for this, we performed an experimental metastasis

749
00:45:42.192 --> 00:45:45.672
assay where we introduced the same cells into the lung,

750
00:45:46.252 --> 00:45:49.762
allowed them to grow to where they demonstrated saturating

751
00:45:49.832 --> 00:45:53.432
luminescence, and then withdrew doxycycline to turn off the

752
00:45:53.492 --> 00:45:56.712
oncogene. So you can see here at day zero where we

753
00:45:56.772 --> 00:45:59.852
withdrew dox, you can see an acute

754
00:46:00.392 --> 00:46:04.372
diminishment in the luminescence signal that sustained over

755
00:46:04.472 --> 00:46:05.372
several months.

756
00:46:07.352 --> 00:46:11.092
In the SOX5 knockout arm, we see a similar diminishment

757
00:46:11.212 --> 00:46:12.152
in the signal of

758
00:46:13.032 --> 00:46:17.012
luminescence signal. But interestingly, you start to see

759
00:46:17.832 --> 00:46:21.532
the signal come back at later time points in this representative

760
00:46:21.632 --> 00:46:22.052
mouse.

761
00:46:23.312 --> 00:46:26.872
And this was also seen across the experiment, as indicated by the

762
00:46:26.912 --> 00:46:28.152
Kaplan-Meier curves,

763
00:46:29.032 --> 00:46:32.312
that loss of SOX5, even at a non-orthotopic site, was

764
00:46:32.372 --> 00:46:34.252
accelerating time to recurrence.

765
00:46:36.732 --> 00:46:40.672
So finally, we wanted to ask if this is related to the ability of tumor

766
00:46:40.692 --> 00:46:43.672
cells to proliferate in this latent phase.

767
00:46:43.732 --> 00:46:47.652
To do so, we used cells from the MTB-TAN mice

768
00:46:47.732 --> 00:46:51.632
containing either a scrambled hairpin or a hairpin

769
00:46:52.232 --> 00:46:54.552
targeting SOX5 to knock down SOX5.

770
00:46:55.132 --> 00:46:58.552
And what you see here is there were no differences in the

771
00:46:58.612 --> 00:47:02.392
Ki-67 prevalence in proliferative time

772
00:47:02.432 --> 00:47:05.092
points. But when you look at the residual lesions,

773
00:47:06.112 --> 00:47:10.012
but most profoundly at the late residual lesions, you see this increase

774
00:47:10.072 --> 00:47:13.372
when you lose SOX5 in the number of tumor cells that are

775
00:47:13.391 --> 00:47:14.271
proliferating.

776
00:47:15.312 --> 00:47:19.172
So taken together, these data suggest to us that loss of SOX5

777
00:47:19.232 --> 00:47:22.532
is promoting recurrence by accelerating

778
00:47:22.632 --> 00:47:24.972
proliferation in this latent window.

779
00:47:25.712 --> 00:47:29.472
Our next question was: how might SOX5 be functioning to do so?

780
00:47:30.032 --> 00:47:33.702
And SOX5 is a transcription factor with very defined developmental

781
00:47:33.832 --> 00:47:37.632
roles, where it has functions in both neural

782
00:47:37.652 --> 00:47:41.032
development as well as in specifying cartilage.

783
00:47:43.272 --> 00:47:47.252
Interestingly, when we looked at gene expression profiles from both in vivo

784
00:47:47.412 --> 00:47:51.102
and in vitro experiments using these MTB-TAN derived

785
00:47:51.172 --> 00:47:54.812
cells, we observed an enrichment of the gene ontology

786
00:47:54.932 --> 00:47:57.592
term ossification in both settings.

787
00:47:58.812 --> 00:48:02.612
Additionally, we also observed enrichment of terms such as endochondral

788
00:48:02.672 --> 00:48:06.532
bone growth, bone mineralization, chondrocyte, and osteoblast

789
00:48:06.612 --> 00:48:07.592
differentiation.

790
00:48:08.412 --> 00:48:11.952
And this was really striking to us because we were looking at pure mammary

791
00:48:12.012 --> 00:48:15.932
epithelial cell populations in vitro as well as in vivo,

792
00:48:15.992 --> 00:48:19.832
where the cells were sorted based on a GFP label they

793
00:48:19.912 --> 00:48:20.292
had.

794
00:48:21.552 --> 00:48:25.012
So it suggested that mammary epithelial cells were undergoing a

795
00:48:25.052 --> 00:48:28.512
differentiation event that might render them more

796
00:48:28.552 --> 00:48:32.012
mesodermal in nature. But we wanted to confirm the

797
00:48:32.032 --> 00:48:34.332
prediction from the gene expression here.

798
00:48:35.852 --> 00:48:39.492
And to do this, we decided to use alcian blue and Von Kossa

799
00:48:39.612 --> 00:48:43.192
staining, which is normally used to look at endochondral

800
00:48:43.292 --> 00:48:47.272
ossification in embryonic development.

801
00:48:47.772 --> 00:48:51.732
So what is this process? Endochondral ossification is a

802
00:48:51.792 --> 00:48:55.772
process wherein you require a cartilage template to

803
00:48:55.832 --> 00:48:59.472
form bone, and this is visualized histologically using

804
00:48:59.552 --> 00:49:02.932
alcian blue and Von Kossa staining.Alcian blue

805
00:49:03.552 --> 00:49:07.392
is a stain that marks proteoglycans that are abundantly

806
00:49:07.452 --> 00:49:10.911
made by chondrocytes. And if you remember, it's also the

807
00:49:11.712 --> 00:49:15.632
sugar modified molecules that we had previously identified in RTCs as

808
00:49:15.712 --> 00:49:17.572
being essential for their survival.

809
00:49:18.572 --> 00:49:22.392
Von Kossa staining marks the calcified areas in the bone and is

810
00:49:22.452 --> 00:49:25.872
basically silver nitrate that replaces calcium phosphate.

811
00:49:26.692 --> 00:49:30.392
So we first wanted to use this histological approach to confirm the gene

812
00:49:30.432 --> 00:49:31.632
expression findings

813
00:49:32.632 --> 00:49:33.612
that we saw.

814
00:49:35.092 --> 00:49:38.872
So as a positive control here, I used an embryonic day 16.5

815
00:49:38.992 --> 00:49:42.912
embryo and looked at Von Kossa staining and Alcian

816
00:49:42.992 --> 00:49:46.412
blue staining and confirmed that this is indeed marking

817
00:49:46.732 --> 00:49:49.832
the calcified areas as well as cartilage.

818
00:49:50.752 --> 00:49:54.672
We then looked at the staining pattern in primary tumors where we

819
00:49:54.712 --> 00:49:56.212
observed negligible staining.

820
00:49:57.252 --> 00:50:00.772
However, when you look at residual lesions, you see an abundance of

821
00:50:00.792 --> 00:50:04.332
proteoglycans being expressed, as well as Von

822
00:50:04.392 --> 00:50:08.372
Kossa staining begin to appear in a temporal manner, really

823
00:50:08.412 --> 00:50:11.912
confirming what the gene expression data were telling us, that there is this

824
00:50:12.032 --> 00:50:14.592
ossification-like process occurring.

825
00:50:17.572 --> 00:50:21.392
To further confirm this, we wanted to use small animal imaging, for which

826
00:50:21.472 --> 00:50:25.312
we chose to use a PET/CT approach. For PET, we

827
00:50:25.392 --> 00:50:29.372
used 18F sodium fluoride as our positron emitting tracer,

828
00:50:30.032 --> 00:50:33.672
and 18F sodium fluoride marks hydroxyapatite in the bone

829
00:50:34.092 --> 00:50:37.712
and is a very specific marker for the skeleton.

830
00:50:38.952 --> 00:50:42.892
With CT, we used X-rays to look at radiodense areas

831
00:50:43.032 --> 00:50:45.152
in the skeleton. And I hope you can

832
00:50:46.052 --> 00:50:49.612
see here that those two signals are almost indistinguishable.

833
00:50:49.672 --> 00:50:52.712
So the heat map here shows you PET tracer uptake

834
00:50:53.252 --> 00:50:55.632
overlaid on top of the CT signal.

835
00:50:57.632 --> 00:51:00.812
So what you're looking at here is actually from a tumor-bearing mouse.

836
00:51:01.532 --> 00:51:05.132
In these regions marked by the red dotted lines, that's the

837
00:51:05.512 --> 00:51:09.312
orthotopic mammary glands where we can see some PET tracer uptake.

838
00:51:09.812 --> 00:51:13.772
But because that was really hard for us to resolve from the knee joint, we

839
00:51:13.812 --> 00:51:17.012
decided to excise the glands from tracer injected

840
00:51:17.192 --> 00:51:19.772
animals and perform PET/CT ex vivo,

841
00:51:21.232 --> 00:51:22.672
which is what you're looking at here.

842
00:51:23.472 --> 00:51:27.152
So in our negative control, which is just medium

843
00:51:27.212 --> 00:51:31.012
injected without cells into the orthotopic site, you don't see

844
00:51:31.052 --> 00:51:34.672
PET tracer uptake. We see minimal PET tracer or

845
00:51:34.752 --> 00:51:37.752
CT signal in two primary tumor time points.

846
00:51:38.332 --> 00:51:42.212
However, when you look at residual lesions, you start to see a progressive increase

847
00:51:42.292 --> 00:51:46.182
in tracer uptake that is coincident with CT signal, seen here in

848
00:51:46.252 --> 00:51:49.172
white and marked with the arrowheads.

849
00:51:49.852 --> 00:51:53.352
Suggesting that this is a phenomenon that's occurring and it's getting

850
00:51:53.372 --> 00:51:56.831
aggravated during late residual lesion time points.

851
00:51:59.672 --> 00:52:03.552
And this is perhaps best exemplified by sections that we got

852
00:52:03.612 --> 00:52:07.132
from recurrences where we could still see a remnant residual

853
00:52:07.192 --> 00:52:10.592
lesion. So what you're looking at here in the H&amp;E is a more

854
00:52:10.692 --> 00:52:14.192
eosinophilic area marked with the black dotted line,

855
00:52:14.812 --> 00:52:18.492
where we saw Alcian blue and Von Kossa staining.

856
00:52:19.772 --> 00:52:23.592
And if we looked at serial sections from this tumor, you can

857
00:52:23.712 --> 00:52:26.932
see that that eosinophilic area has very minimal

858
00:52:27.052 --> 00:52:30.812
Ki67 staining, as well as 24-hour EdU

859
00:52:30.892 --> 00:52:34.192
uptake, suggesting that the tumor cells in that area are

860
00:52:34.292 --> 00:52:37.912
actually low proliferating compared to the mass around it.

861
00:52:38.392 --> 00:52:41.301
Again, driving home that inverse correlation between

862
00:52:41.332 --> 00:52:44.352
ossification and proliferation.

863
00:52:46.552 --> 00:52:49.812
And then our burning question really was, is this actually regulated by

864
00:52:49.852 --> 00:52:53.612
SOX5 in the residual lesions? To do this, we used the

865
00:52:53.652 --> 00:52:57.562
knockdown cells that I previously described with

866
00:52:57.592 --> 00:53:01.092
the hairpins, and we found that loss of SOX5

867
00:53:01.132 --> 00:53:05.081
massively decreased the calcification and PET tracer uptake that

868
00:53:05.132 --> 00:53:07.902
we normally see in the residual lesions in the control.

869
00:53:08.472 --> 00:53:12.392
And this is quantified here on the right where you see a substantial decrease

870
00:53:12.492 --> 00:53:13.092
in signal.

871
00:53:15.252 --> 00:53:18.051
And then finally we asked, is this relevant to patients?

872
00:53:18.592 --> 00:53:22.431
So in the neoadjuvant therapy data sets that Lewis previously described,

873
00:53:22.991 --> 00:53:26.312
we asked if we see an adaptive increase in chondrogenesis and

874
00:53:26.352 --> 00:53:30.072
osteogenesis gene expression signatures, which when

875
00:53:30.132 --> 00:53:32.132
significant is highlighted here in pink.

876
00:53:32.572 --> 00:53:36.372
And we did indeed see this in both estrogen receptor negative as well as

877
00:53:36.412 --> 00:53:39.112
estrogen receptor positive patient data sets.

878
00:53:40.832 --> 00:53:44.372
And in a subset of these patients for whom we had both post neoadjuvant

879
00:53:44.432 --> 00:53:44.952
therapy

880
00:53:45.812 --> 00:53:49.692
gene expression data as well as long-term recurrence outcomes,

881
00:53:50.112 --> 00:53:53.952
we found that enrichment of these signatures was associated with a

882
00:53:53.972 --> 00:53:57.852
delay in time to recurrence. Again, speaking to the

883
00:53:57.912 --> 00:54:01.492
fact that these signatures are associated with indolent

884
00:54:01.652 --> 00:54:02.652
disease progression.

885
00:54:04.792 --> 00:54:07.892
To summarize what I showed you, SOX5 loss promotes RTC

886
00:54:07.972 --> 00:54:10.492
proliferation and accelerates recurrence.

887
00:54:11.252 --> 00:54:14.452
It also impairs chondrogenic and osteogenic

888
00:54:14.512 --> 00:54:18.132
differentiation. We found a surprising dormant residual

889
00:54:18.192 --> 00:54:22.052
lesion phenomenon where you see SOX5 regulated endochondral

890
00:54:22.072 --> 00:54:25.332
ossification, and that this osteochondrogenic gene

891
00:54:25.392 --> 00:54:29.252
expression is associated with improved recurrence-free survival

892
00:54:29.292 --> 00:54:30.092
in patients.

893
00:54:31.292 --> 00:54:35.252
So there are several details in this story that I didn't have time to get to, but

894
00:54:35.292 --> 00:54:38.592
here's a QR code that would take you to the paper that just came out

895
00:54:38.792 --> 00:54:41.612
in April's issue of Cancer Discovery.

896
00:54:42.712 --> 00:54:46.472
And with that, I'd like to thank Lewis, the members of the

897
00:54:46.512 --> 00:54:50.332
Chodosh Lab, our collaborators in radiology, the

898
00:54:50.372 --> 00:54:54.332
Department of Cancer Biology for always being so supportive, and

899
00:54:54.372 --> 00:54:57.212
my former funding sources. Thank you.

900
00:55:02.552 --> 00:55:05.131
We have time for some questions

901
00:55:08.440 --> 00:55:11.760
We see microcalcifications in breast tissue very commonly

902
00:55:12.180 --> 00:55:14.640
associated with ductal carcinoma in situ.

903
00:55:14.680 --> 00:55:18.540
The calcifications are different than benign calcifications, and radiologists can

904
00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:21.380
identify them. Do you think that that phenomenon could be occurring in

905
00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:24.759
pre-neoplasia as well as the inflammatory recurrence disease?

906
00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:28.760
I think that's a great question. This has come up before, especially because

907
00:55:28.800 --> 00:55:32.520
mammograms can quite routinely detect microcalcifications.

908
00:55:33.020 --> 00:55:36.880
Whether that is the same process or, as you mentioned, it's very

909
00:55:36.900 --> 00:55:40.760
dependent on the type of calcification and the properties associated

910
00:55:40.800 --> 00:55:43.140
with it as to whether it gets called

911
00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:47.580
relevant to disease or requiring further management.

912
00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:52.640
We would propose that this is part of an active program of

913
00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:56.340
differentiation compared to calcification, which can also occur

914
00:55:56.980 --> 00:56:00.360
in an independent manner, for example, if you have necrosis or

915
00:56:00.440 --> 00:56:04.240
even from milk in the ducts. So it would require

916
00:56:04.280 --> 00:56:08.040
additional study to ask if there is maybe an association with a

917
00:56:08.080 --> 00:56:11.990
chondrogenic phenotype as well that might lead to more of a

918
00:56:12.020 --> 00:56:14.720
hypothesis related to what we're seeing in indolence.

919
00:56:18.540 --> 00:56:22.100
Thank you. Great talk. I have a question that is related.

920
00:56:22.460 --> 00:56:26.260
Did you try to see if there is a correlation between the chondrogenic

921
00:56:26.360 --> 00:56:29.900
signature and H&amp;E images from the

922
00:56:30.240 --> 00:56:32.600
samples collected from those tumors?

923
00:56:33.520 --> 00:56:34.650
From patient samples, you mean?

924
00:56:34.650 --> 00:56:35.960
Yeah, from patient samples.

925
00:56:36.600 --> 00:56:38.640
That's something we're actually in the process of doing.

926
00:56:38.740 --> 00:56:42.600
We have access to patient samples, and we're

927
00:56:42.640 --> 00:56:46.220
trying to see if we can identify, as predicted by the gene

928
00:56:46.260 --> 00:56:50.160
expression signatures, are we also able to look for these features there.

929
00:56:50.620 --> 00:56:50.999
Thank you.

930
00:56:54.700 --> 00:56:58.400
Hi there. Thanks for the great talk and very interesting work.

931
00:56:59.040 --> 00:57:02.900
I'm wondering if you know what the exact link is between

932
00:57:02.980 --> 00:57:06.050
loss of SOX5 and enhancement of

933
00:57:06.140 --> 00:57:10.080
proliferation. What part of the cell cycle machinery does

934
00:57:10.140 --> 00:57:12.280
loss of SOX5 ultimately

935
00:57:13.180 --> 00:57:13.620
drive?

936
00:57:13.850 --> 00:57:13.850
Mm-hmm.

937
00:57:13.860 --> 00:57:15.580
And then if there's time, I'll have a second question.

938
00:57:15.780 --> 00:57:16.020
Okay.

939
00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:18.220
That's a good question, actually.

940
00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:21.520
There are many parts of the study that require further

941
00:57:21.580 --> 00:57:25.500
elucidation mechanistically, including how SOX5 is being

942
00:57:25.540 --> 00:57:28.340
temporally regulated, that we don't have a good handle on.

943
00:57:29.760 --> 00:57:31.300
It's interesting you mention that.

944
00:57:31.360 --> 00:57:35.200
There are contexts in which SOX5 has been

945
00:57:35.280 --> 00:57:38.720
studied predominantly for its oncogenic functions.

946
00:57:40.060 --> 00:57:43.980
One that is more similar to what we see with quiescence is actually in

947
00:57:44.020 --> 00:57:47.340
the context of neurogenesis, where loss of

948
00:57:47.360 --> 00:57:50.610
SOX5 can promote a proliferative burst and

949
00:57:50.900 --> 00:57:53.120
deplete neural progenitor cells.

950
00:57:53.900 --> 00:57:57.700
Why that context matters and what it's actually doing to the cell cycle

951
00:57:57.740 --> 00:58:01.420
remains to be studied, but I think constitute important questions

952
00:58:01.480 --> 00:58:02.020
here.

953
00:58:02.060 --> 00:58:02.970
Thanks. I think I'll let the other person go.

954
00:58:02.970 --> 00:58:05.400
One last question, which will be the person behind you.

955
00:58:07.620 --> 00:58:08.180
Great talk.

956
00:58:08.300 --> 00:58:08.350
Thanks.

957
00:58:08.440 --> 00:58:12.160
So one question for the preclinical translation

958
00:58:12.240 --> 00:58:16.200
aspect is, beyond the genetic SOX5 knockdown

959
00:58:16.660 --> 00:58:17.360
or knockout,

960
00:58:18.220 --> 00:58:21.400
is there anything on market for the osteogenesis

961
00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:25.820
blocking at the residual state that you could do in vivo

962
00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:28.240
or preclinically?

963
00:58:29.420 --> 00:58:33.380
Yeah. So I think the proposal or the best approach would

964
00:58:33.420 --> 00:58:37.160
be the opposite. If we could try and actually enrich this

965
00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:40.500
program and maintain cells in a dormant state, that would be

966
00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:44.489
great. We don't know how to go about that yet, but actually, as I

967
00:58:44.520 --> 00:58:48.040
mentioned in the previous response, having a better

968
00:58:48.080 --> 00:58:51.920
handle on how SOX5 is being temporally activated would

969
00:58:51.960 --> 00:58:55.660
get us there. So that's future directions and things we're working

970
00:58:55.680 --> 00:58:56.860
on.

971
00:58:56.920 --> 00:59:00.080
And with that, we'll thank Dr. Srikumar for an excellent talk.

972
00:59:04.440 --> 00:59:08.220
Our next speaker, we're honored, came all the way from Germany, across the

973
00:59:08.300 --> 00:59:11.060
ocean for this. We are honored to have Dr.

974
00:59:11.300 --> 00:59:15.260
Christoph Klein, who will bring things home by telling us

975
00:59:15.300 --> 00:59:18.970
things that probably most of us here don't know about the molecular

976
00:59:19.040 --> 00:59:21.160
characteristics of human DTCs.

977
00:59:22.580 --> 00:59:25.680
Yeah. Thank you very much for this invitation here.

978
00:59:26.820 --> 00:59:30.520
You learned yesterday evening, MRD is a hot topic since

979
00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:33.820
three years. I was surprised to learn this,

980
00:59:34.800 --> 00:59:36.560
because actually the study

981
00:59:37.600 --> 00:59:41.280
of the seed of metastasis is actually much

982
00:59:41.360 --> 00:59:41.760
older.

983
00:59:42.680 --> 00:59:46.600
So in 1987, Gertrud Müller had a wonderful idea,

984
00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:51.000
which is still used today, to use cytokeratin and

985
00:59:51.060 --> 00:59:54.740
EpCAM as markers to detect disseminated tumor

986
00:59:54.800 --> 00:59:56.640
cells in bone marrow.

987
00:59:57.640 --> 01:00:01.560
And as it has been explained, and I will not go deeper in

988
01:00:01.620 --> 01:00:05.480
this, this is an opportunity, after surgery

989
01:00:05.600 --> 01:00:09.300
or local treatment, to prevent relapses that may

990
01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:11.680
arise from disseminated cancer cells.

991
01:00:13.200 --> 01:00:14.520
This research has gone

992
01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:17.940
forward. Many patients have been screened.

993
01:00:18.020 --> 01:00:20.060
Also, this data has been shown before.

